{
  "doc_id": "60555",
  "text": "Multiple myeloma (MM) remains an incurable hematologic malignancy in spite of the development of various antimyeloma agents. In the early days, alkylating agents such as melphalan or cyclophosphamide were used, but improving the prognosis of MM patients was not satisfactory due to the low efficacy of therapy with an isolated alkylating agent [CITATION_1] . By the 1990s, high-dose melphalan chemotherapy followed by autologous hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (ASCT) was introduced. This strategy improved the overall response and survival of MM patients, but the benefits of high-dose chemotherapy and ASCT were limited to younger patients due to the significant toxicity of this therapy [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
